		<item>
		<title>4 Ways to Pinpoint Your Targeting with Google Ads Custom Audiences</title>
		<link>https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/04/19/google-custom-audiences</link>
					<comments>https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/04/19/google-custom-audiences#respond</comments>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Michelle Morgan]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Mon, 19 Apr 2021 05:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Display Ads]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/04/19/google-custom-audiences/</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>In the recent past, Google has combined Custom¬†Affinity Audiences and Custom Intent Audiences into one: Custom Audiences. Learn about how to target your ads based on interest/behavior, type of websites browsed, types of apps downloaded, and even physical location visited.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/04/19/google-custom-audiences">4 Ways to Pinpoint Your Targeting with Google Ads Custom Audiences</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<section class="section">
<div class="section__inner section__inner--column_seperator">
<div class="column">
<div>
<div class="tag">
<p>Over the years, we see many different features in Google Ads. Some things come, then they leave, and other times we get adjusted versions of what they used to be.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="column">
<p>One such feature that has changed relatively recently is the types of targeting options on the Display Network.</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="a0263f6b-72b6-4232-b22e-07621b1f98db" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/audience-targeting-psychographics-1.jpg" alt="psychographics image" width="693" height="462" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>In particular, Custom Intent Audiences and Custom¬†Affinity Audiences have been combined into Custom Audiences.</p>
<p>Rather than choosing from a preset list of options from Google, we‚Äôre able to create our own audiences based on their interests and, in some instances, their search history.¬†I&#8217;ve really come to enjoy using <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/content-distribution">Custom Audiences</a>, so¬†I want¬†to take the time and walk you through all of the options available for you to leverage for better ad performance. They include:</p>
<ul>
<li>Interest &amp; behavior</li>
<li>Types of websites browsed</li>
<li>Types of apps downloaded</li>
<li>Category of physical location visited</li>
</ul>
<h2>What are the Custom Audience options in Google Ads?</h2>
<p>Custom Audiences are used for display and YouTube ads. Let&#8217;s go through what each targeting type means and how it can be used. I&#8217;ll also provide strategies for getting the most out of them and show you how to set up Custom Audiences in your account for <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/google-ads-audience-targeting">better audience targeting</a>.</p>
<h3>1. Interest and¬†behavior targeting</h3>
<p>The first box we‚Äôre presented with is to target users based on their interests or <a href="/blog/ws/2017/08/28/behavioral-segmentation">behaviors</a>. When you hover over the support box, here‚Äôs the description Google gives:</p>
<p><em>‚ÄúEnter interests, in the form of keywords or phrases, that represent your ideal customer. Your ads will reach people likely to be interested in or with purchase intent for your keywords based on their behavior and activities, such as apps they use or the type of content they search for online.‚Äù</em></p>
<p>What we‚Äôre trying to do here is almost use targeting similar to <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2017/08/09/easy-keyword-research-guide">keywords</a> to find users who have either been conducting research around specific topics or have shown interest in a product, solution, service while on Google.</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="e8dd9852-f062-4e4d-8823-a0b69e9532d0" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/making-most-custom-audiences-interest-1.png" alt="google custom audiences‚Äîtarget by interest tab" width="800" height="412" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>For example, if you‚Äôre trying to target users who are looking to buy a used car, you might type in something like ‚Äúbest used cars‚Äù, then Google will show you some other phrases you could target based on what they‚Äôve seen users search for.¬† As you <a href="/blog/ws/2021/02/24/microsoft-advertising-intelligence-tools">add more keywords</a>, you‚Äôll see the Audience Insights chart on the right adjust based on the audience you‚Äôve selected to include.</p>
<p><strong>Google properties vs the Google Display Network</strong></p>
<p>One of the best features of these Custom Audiences is when you plan to use this list on Google-owned properties.</p>
<p>The two buttons at the top of this builder provide a little insight and to build the audience you‚Äôll have to choose one or the other:</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="91904fd7-0a2d-4e88-aeb2-39350a166db4" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/making-most-custom-audiences-any-of-these-interests-1.png" alt="making-most-custom-audiences-interests" width="800" height="96" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>The first option here means that you‚Äôll be <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2019/04/15/audience-targeting">targeting</a> users just as mentioned before: based on their interests and purchase intentions.</p>
<p>But the second option is where things get more interesting: People who searched for any of these terms on Google.</p>
<p>This means you‚Äôre effectively doing<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2016/05/17/remarketing-audiences"> search retargeting</a> for any of the terms you add (and any terms ‚Äúsimilar‚Äù to them) as long as your ad is going to run on a Google-owned property.</p>
<p>Google-owned properties include:</p>
<ul>
<li>YouTube</li>
<li>Google Discover</li>
<li>Gmail</li>
</ul>
<p>Unfortunately, the <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2019/03/14/google-display-network-targeting-facts">Google Display Network</a> is not one of those owned properties. Each website is owned by individual users or companies and has opted into Google AdSense to monetize their site.</p>
<p>In the end, we‚Äôre able to retarget people based on what they searched for on Google, then put our relevant ads in front of them when they are <a href="/blog/ws/2020/05/14/how-to-get-more-views-on-youtube">watching videos on YouTube</a>, checking their email, or discovering new topics on mobile. Pretty powerful stuff!</p>
<h3>2. People who browse types of websites</h3>
<p>Below the keyword section, there is a new header that says ‚ÄúExpand audience by also including‚Äù which is then followed by a list of three additional types of targeting.</p>
<p>The first is People who browse types of websites.</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="cdf01882-8fac-470e-b4e8-9056e8a1e504" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/making-most-custom-audiences-websites-1.png" alt="google custom audiences‚Äîtarget by type of website browsed" width="800" height="159" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>For this section, Google is asking you to provide the types of websites, in URL form, that your target audience would visit. As it mentions, this is not a way to target those specific website placements, but rather to capitalize on the audience insights from those sites to find new users.</p>
<p>If you know the places where your customers hang out online, this can be a very <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2015/01/28/facebook-ad-targeting">powerful type of targeting</a>.</p>
<p>For websites, stay away from broader sites and instead focus on industry-specific and closely related sites. For the used car example above, it‚Äôs a better idea for you to include websites to local used car dealers or larger national used car websites than simply targeting the Ford, Chevrolet, or Volkswagen websites. Sure, users on those sites might be interested in buying a car, but people could have lots of other reasons for visiting those sites than simply buying a used car.</p>
<h3>3. People who use types of apps</h3>
<p>The next targeting option is very similar to the website targeting options, but includes apps instead.</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="3eaa7234-e146-43d3-9580-720329a28e97" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/making-most-custom-audiences-apps-1.png" alt="google custom audiences‚Äîtarget by apps used" width="800" height="174" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>Think of the types of apps your potential customers would use. This could be either a permanently installed app or something more temporary.¬†For my used car example, these apps are likely going to be more temporary as you no longer need them after you‚Äôve made the purchase.</p>
<p>To get started, I type in a few companies I know that are important to many users when trying to find a used car:</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="bf2dff8c-0621-4ad8-b165-eeaa0bdb9fe2" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/making-most-custom-audiences-kelley-blue-book-1.png" alt="google custom audiences‚Äîexample of app targeting, apps similar to kelley blue book" width="600" height="441" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>As I type in the names, Google automatically populates a list and suggests apps I should add based on the themes I‚Äôm working with.</p>
<p>I can keep using apps that are similar to Kelley Blue Book, which helps you determine the value of a used car. Or I could take a different tack and include apps like Credit Karma which might also find users who are trying to ensure their credit is good enough to purchase a car.</p>
<p>Think of the different types of apps users might use to either help them make a purchase or show interest in your <a href="/blog/ws/2020/07/29/how-to-promote-a-product">product or service</a> and how you can leverage those for Custom Audience building.</p>
<h3>4. People who visited certain places</h3>
<p>The last type of targeting option is focused on the types of places your customers have visited recently.</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="5533eca0-a338-469f-b155-975db3e2f7a0" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/making-most-custom-audiences-places-1.png" alt="google custom audiences‚Äîtargeting places visited" width="800" height="168" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>These are going to be categories of physical locations rather than the individual places themselves, but these can be immensely useful depending on who you‚Äôre trying to reach.</p>
<p>For my used car example, I conducted two quick searches:</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="af4173b5-7744-41e0-9dc8-f2b8bfcf79dc" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/making-most-custom-audiences-used-car-1.png" alt="google custom audiences‚Äîtargeting places a person searching for a used car would visit" width="800" height="454" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>Each of these opened up physical locations that could be quite valuable. Used Car Dealers is highly relevant for my purposes off of the ‚Äúused car‚Äù search, but even on the more general ‚Äúcar dealership‚Äù search, there are some interesting options around specific brands. If my hypothetical used car dealership only dealt with one brand, or if I‚Äôm the manager of the used car business at a specific brand‚Äôs dealership, these could also be great options to target.</p>
<h2>How do I set up a Custom Audience?</h2>
<p>The name <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2017/12/11/facebook-custom-audience-strategy">Custom Audiences</a> might suggest that you would build these in your audience manager, but that‚Äôs actually not the case.</p>
<p>To build Custom Audiences, you‚Äôll need to start by either creating a new <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2019/05/23/google-display-ads">display</a> or <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2019/02/13/youtube-ad-placements">video campaign</a> or navigating to an existing ad group where you can leverage audiences.</p>
<p>Once you‚Äôre in the Audiences tab, click the blue plus button.</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="0eee4ff6-889c-4bdc-98df-7b947cfe0c55" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/make-the-most-of-custom-audiences-add-filter-1.png" alt="google custom audiences‚Äîadd audience button in google ads" width="800" height="186" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>Toward the bottom of the list, you‚Äôll see Custom Audiences as an option.</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="724bc1e3-b1b5-40d7-84ba-10ea281def65" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/making-most-custom-audiences-targeting-1.png" alt="google custom audiences‚Äîcustom audience option in google ads" width="564" height="734" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>If you have Custom Audiences created, you‚Äôll be able to choose them from the list at the top. If you don‚Äôt, then you can create a new one by choosing ‚Äú+ Custom Audience‚Äù at the bottom of the list.</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="b3192548-f870-4c0a-96e0-732ca7c52f9f" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/making-most-custom-audiences-add-audience-1.png" alt="google custom audiences add custom audience option in google ads" width="464" height="690" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>Then you‚Äôll be provided with this audience builder.</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="edec3d74-5613-40ec-bfab-39ff999bff1a" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/making-most-custom-audiences-new-custom-audience-1.png" alt="google custom audiences‚Äînew custom audience tab in google ads" width="800" height="465" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<h2>Go beyond the keyword with Custom Audiences</h2>
<p>Although Google targeting options continue to change with some frequency, I think we‚Äôre in a great spot to leverage Custom Audiences right now. There are many different targeting options that go beyond broad interests. We effectively have Search Retargeting across the Google-owned network, but we can also target people based on specific websites, apps, and physical locations they‚Äôve visited. Talk about going beyond the keyword. Next time you‚Äôre looking to spruce up your targeting on Google, don‚Äôt miss out on testing Custom Audiences to see how they can work for you.</p>
</div>
<div class="column">
<div class="views-element-container contextual-region"></div>
</div>
</div>
</section>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
